Do Overdraft infocards help users top-up and avoid arrears? (Part II)

In order to answer the question above, we ran 3 A/B test experiments:

  • Sixty days usage infocard test - Displays information that users started using their arranged overdraft, and is meant to be displayed a repeated time 60 days after it was last shown if applicable
  • Fifty percent usage infocard test - Displays information that users have crossed 50% of their arranged overdraft limit. In this test we have 2 variants:
    • One infocard that displays the amount of overdraft users
    • One infocard that displays that they are using 50% of their overdraft limit
  • Quarterly top-up infocard test - Displays information that users will be charged their overdraft in one week, sent quarterly (since overdraft interest is changed quarterly)

Here you can find the designs used for each of these infocards.

Experimental Design ¶

For each of the infocards we want to test, users that meet the infocart trigger conditions will be randomly split into 2 groups:

  • One control group that will not receive the infocard
  • One variant group that will receive the infocard

This split was automatically handled by plutonium (the overdraft microservice) as soon as the users met the trigger condition.

Hypothesis ¶

For each of the experiments, we have 2 success measures, so we'll be defining hypothesis for each of these:

Top-up rates increase

  • H0: There are no significant differences in top-up rate within 7 days of meeting the trigger condition
  • H1: The top-up rates for the variant group are significantly higher than the control group within 7 days of meeting the trigger condition

Arrears rates decrease

  • H0: There are no significant differences in arrears rates within 3 months of meeting the trigger condition
  • H1: The arrears rates for the variant group are significantly lower than the control group within 3 months of meeting the trigger condition

Write-off rates decrease

  • H0: There are no significant differences in write-off rates within 6 months of meeting the trigger condition
  • H1: The write-off rates for the variant group are significantly lower than the control group within 6 months of meeting the trigger condition

Experiment Analysis & Timings ¶

In the part I of the analysis of this experiment, run in June 2021 you can find the top-up rates and preliminary arrears results for the sixty days usage infocard and fifty percent usage infocard. For the conclusions of this experiment, we will consider the top-up results from the first part of the results (since there were no visible changes in these since then), and the remaining conclusions will come from this second part of the research. Here you can find a summary of the main results from both experiments combined.

We will be running a Z-Test for each of the experiments and success measures, and assume a significance level of 0.05.

For the sixty day usage and fifty percent usage experiments, they all started at 2021-04-29 and ended at different times, depending on the necessary time to evaluate after the results (for top-ups we kept our first results from June, and needed 3 months for arrears and 6 months for write-offs). Therefore, the top-ups end date is 2021-06-04, the arrears end date is 2021-09-30 and the write-offs end date is 2021-06-30.

For quarterly top-ups, since these are only sent once each quarter, we’re considering results from end of Q2 and end of Q3 for top-ups and arrears, and only end of Q2 for write-offs.

Key take-aways: ¶

Sixty Day Infocard Experiment: ¶

  • We have significantly higher top-up rates for the variant group in all tests of the sixty day experiment. This means that for all users that received the infocars, we verified a 1 percentage point increase in top-up rates for users that received the infocard (from 67.8% to 68.8%).
  • However, here we didn’t see any significant decreases in the arrears or write-off rates.
  • Recommendation : Given that top-up rates results for this experiment were quite positive, we would recommend adopting this infocard moving forward.

Fifty Percent Infocard Experiment: ¶

  • Here we didn’t see any significant decreases in the top-up or write-off rates for both variants of this experiment.
  • We see a significant decrease in arrears rates for all users in the percent variant, but not when filtering for users who logged in the app. Based on that, the percent variant seems to perform slightly better than the amount variant.
  • Recommendation : Since we didn't find a consistently favorable trend for variant users in this experiment (neither for top-up rates nor arrears rates), we don’t discourage the usage of this infocard, but we would recommend re-running this experiment at a higher usage threshold.

Quarterly Top-up Infocard Experiment: ¶

  • For all users that received the infocards, we verified a 0.9 percentage point increase in top-up rates for variant users (from 50.2% to 51.1%).
  • Here we didn’t see any significant decreases in the write-off rates. We see a significant decrease in arrears rates for all users, but not when filtering for users who logged in the app.
  • Recommendation : Given that top-up rates results for this experiment were quite positive, we would recommend adopting this infocard moving forward.

For some of the arrears rates for the comparison of Viewed inforcard (vs. login in control) and Clicked inforcard (vs. login in control), we found some undesirable cases where the variant arrears were significantly higher than control. Given that these variant users are being compared against a different control group (since control users didn't receive an infocard that could be viewed/ clicked), and these arrears results don't seem to materialize into significant write-off differences, we will not be considering these results in the following conclusions.

Top-up Z-Test results for the Sixty Day Reminder Infocard ¶

test larger_p_value smaller_p_value result
0 All users with top-up 0.01 0.99 Variant top-up rates are significantly higher than the control (reject H0)
1 Users that logged-in 0.01 0.99 Variant top-up rates are significantly higher than the control (reject H0)
2 Viewed inforcard (vs. login in control) 1.00 0.00 Samples have similar top-up rates (fail to reject H0)
3 Clicked inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.00 1.00 Variant top-up rates are significantly higher than the control (reject H0)

Conclusion: We have significantly higher top-up rates for the variant group in almost all tests of the quarterly top-up experiment (except for users who viewed the infocard). This means that for all users that received the infocards, we verified a 0.9 percentage point increase in top-up rates for variant users (from 50.2% to 51.1%)

Arrears Z-Test results for the Sixty Day Reminder Infocard ¶

test larger_p_value smaller_p_value result
0 All users with top-up 0.96 0.04 Variant arrears rates are significantly lower than the control (reject H0)
1 Users that logged-in 0.92 0.08 Samples have similar arrears rates (fail to reject H0)
2 Viewed inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.00 1.00 Variant arrears rates are significantly higher the control (reject H0 but undesirable effect)
3 Clicked inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.69 0.31 Samples have similar arrears rates (fail to reject H0)

Conclusion: With a decrease of 0.4 percentage points from 15.7% to 15.2%, we have significant lower arrears rates for the variant group in the quarterly top-up experiment for all users. Also, for the variant users who viewed the infocard vs. login users in control, we seem to have an undesirable significant increase of 1 percentage point.

Arrears Z-Test results for the Percent Reminder Infocard ¶

test larger_p_value smaller_p_value result
0 All users with top-up 0.99 0.01 Variant arrears rates are significantly lower than the control (reject H0)
1 Users that logged-in 0.92 0.08 Samples have similar arrears rates (fail to reject H0)
2 Viewed inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.03 0.97 Variant arrears rates are significantly higher the control (reject H0 but undesirable effect)
3 Clicked inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.00 1.00 Variant arrears rates are significantly higher the control (reject H0 but undesirable effect)

Conclusion: Here we have somewhat contradictory results, with a significant decrease for all variant users of 0.7 percentage points, no significant changes for users that logged-in, and undesirable significantly higher arrears rates for the variant groups who either viewed or clicked the infocard (with increases of 0.5 percentage points and 3.4 percentage points respectively).

test larger_p_value smaller_p_value result

3 Clicked inforcard (vs. login in control) 0.00 1.00 Variant arrears rates are significantly higher the control (reject H0 but undesirable effect)

Conclusion: And here we find no significant differences between variant and control in the all users and users who logged in groups, but we do have undesirable significantly higher arrears rates for the variant groups who either viewed or clicked the infocard (with increases of 0.9 percentage points and 4.3 percentage points respectively).
